. Bill To Enable Agency Meet International Standard ABUJA – The Senate on Wednesday moved to provide effective air navigation services in Nigeria. This followed the passage of the Nigerian Airspace Management Agency Bill 2022 which seeks to repeal the Nigerian Airspace Management Agency Act 2010. UPDATED: Senate Backtracks On Direct Primaries, Adopts Indirect… BREAKING: Senate Backtracks On Direct Primaries The passage of the bill is sequel to the consideration of a report by the Committee on Aviation led by Senator Smart Adeyemi (Kogi West). In his remarks, President of the Senate, Ahmad Lawan, said that “the issues that surround the Bill are significant in ensuring safe air travels and are part of efforts at enhancing the health and profitability of the overarching aviation sector and public benefit”, he said. He observed that the Act establishing NAMA came into effect on May 26, 1999, and has been in operation for twenty-two years. He added that the amendments to the NAMA Act 2010 are geared towards aligning the Agency to meet new operational requirements in the industry as stipulated by the International Civil Aviation Organization (ICAO). The NAMA bill is one of the six Aviation Executive Bills referred to the Committee by the Senate which are related to crucial matters of regulation, training, management, and safety of the Aviation Industry.